    title: "Student Accommodation Melbourne 2025: Complete Cost, Areas & Tips Guide",
    slug: "student-accommodation-melbourne-2025-guide-2",
    excerpt: "Find affordable student accommodation in Melbourne 2025. Compare costs, best areas, booking tips & hidden fees. Guide for Indian & international students.",
    content: "<h2>Why Melbourne? The Student City at a Glance</h2><p>Melbourne hosts over <strong>180,000 international students</strong>, making it Australia's premier education destination. The University of Melbourne, RMIT, Monash, and La Trobe attract thousands of Indian students annually\u2014approximately <strong>45,000 Indian students</strong> are currently enrolled across these institutions. Unlike Sydney's expensive reputation, Melbourne offers better value for quality accommodation while maintaining world-class universities.</p><h2>Types of Student Accommodation Melbourne 2025</h2><h3>University Halls of Residence</h3><ul><li><strong>Cost:</strong> AUD $250\u2013450/week (\u20b912,500\u201322,500)</li><li><strong>Pros:</strong> All-inclusive utilities, community, security, convenient location</li><li><strong>Cons:</strong> Limited availability, strict rules, early application deadlines (Jan\u2013March for Feb intake)</li><li><strong>Examples:</strong> UniLodge, IQ Student Accommodation, Scape</li></ul><h3>Purpose-Built Student Accommodation (PBSA)</h3><ul><li><strong>Cost:</strong> AUD $300\u2013500/week (\u20b915,000\u201325,000)</li><li><strong>Pros:</strong> Modern facilities, furnished, flexible leases, furnished study spaces</li><li><strong>Cons:</strong> Premium pricing, long waiting lists during peak season</li></ul><h3>Shared Flats & Houses</h3><ul><li><strong>Cost:</strong> AUD $200\u2013350/week (\u20b910,000\u201317,500)</li><li><strong>Pros:</strong> Most affordable, authentic local experience, flexible terms</li><li><strong>Cons:</strong> Landlord-dependent, utilities variable, less security</li></ul><h3>Homestay</h3><ul><li><strong>Cost:</strong> AUD $280\u2013400/week (\u20b914,000\u201320,000)</li><li><strong>Pros:</strong> Cultural immersion, meals included, instant support system</li><li><strong>Cons:</strong> Less independence, house rules, limited privacy</li></ul><h2>Realistic Rent Ranges Melbourne 2025</h2><table><tr><th>Area Type</th><th>Weekly AUD</th><th>Monthly INR</th><th>Best For</th></tr><tr><td>CBD/Inner</td><td>$350\u2013550</td><td>\u20b91,40,000\u20132,20,000</td><td>Proximity to universities</td></tr><tr><td>Inner Suburbs</td><td>$250\u2013400</td><td>\u20b91,00,000\u20131,60,000</td><td>Balance of cost & access</td></tr><tr><td>Outer Suburbs</td><td>$180\u2013280</td><td>\u20b972,000\u20131,12,000</td><td>Budget-conscious students</td></tr></table><h2>Best Student Areas in Melbourne 2025</h2><h3>1. Fitzroy</h3><p><strong>Rent:</strong> AUD $280\u2013380/week (\u20b914,000\u201319,000) | <strong>Transport:</strong> 10 mins to city | <strong>Vibe:</strong> Bohemian, cafes, affordable. Safe during day; less so late nights.</p><h3>2. Carlton</h3><p><strong>Rent:</strong> AUD $250\u2013350/week (\u20b912,500\u201317,500) | <strong>Transport:</strong> 5 mins to University of Melbourne | <strong>Vibe:</strong> Student hub, Italian Quarter, cultural. Very safe, walkable.</p><h3>3. Southbank</h3><p><strong>Rent:</strong> AUD $350\u2013480/week (\u20b917,500\u201324,000) | <strong>Transport:</strong> Arts/RMIT adjacent | <strong>Vibe:</strong> Premium, riverside, nightlife. Excellent safety, family-friendly.</p><h3>4. Brunswick</h3><p><strong>Rent:</strong> AUD $220\u2013330/week (\u20b911,000\u201316,500) | <strong>Transport:</strong> Tram to city (20 mins) | <strong>Vibe:</strong> Hip, diverse, emerging. Safe, Indian/Asian communities established.</p><h3>5. Footscray</h3><p><strong>Rent:</strong> AUD $180\u2013280/week (\u20b99,000\u201314,000) | <strong>Transport:</strong> 30 mins to CBD | <strong>Vibe:</strong> Affordable, diverse, gentrifying. Moderate safety; check specific streets.</p><h2>What's Typically Included in Rent?</h2><ul><li><strong>Most include:</strong> Furniture, internet, utilities (water, electricity, gas)</li><li><strong>Some exclude:</strong> Electricity surcharges, council tax, parking, internet premium</li><li><strong>Always confirm:</strong> Whether electricity is capped or unlimited</li></ul><h2>How to Book: Timeline & Platforms 2025</h2><p><strong>Best Timing:</strong> Apply 3\u20134 months before intake (November\u2013December for Feb 2025 start; May\u2013June for July start)</p><p><strong>Top Platforms:</strong></p><ul><li>Domain.com.au (private rentals)</li><li>Realestate.com.au (shared flats)</li><li>UniLodge.com.au & Scape.edu.au (official providers)</li><li>Facebook groups ('Melbourne Student Accommodation,' 'RMIT/Monash Housing')</li><li>Flatmates.com.au (room shares)</li></ul><p><strong>Red Flags:</strong> Requests for payment before viewing, no lease agreement, landlord unresponsive, prices 30% below market.</p><h2>Hidden Costs: Budget Beyond Rent</h2><ul><li><strong>Bond/Deposit:</strong> 4 weeks' rent (AUD $800\u20132,200 | \u20b940,000\u20131,10,000)\u2014refundable if undamaged</li><li><strong>Council Tax:</strong> AUD $80\u2013120/month (\u20b94,000\u20136,000)\u2014council charges for property</li><li><strong>Electricity Overage:</strong> AUD $20\u201340/month (\u20b91,000\u20132,000) if not capped</li><li><strong>Guarantor Fee:</strong> Some landlords require guarantor (covered by parents)</li><li><strong>Internet Setup:</strong> AUD $50\u2013100 once (\u20b92,500\u20135,000)</li><li><strong>Contents Insurance:<",
