    id: "1917",
    title: "GRE vs GMAT for Indian Students Abroad 2025: Which Test is Right?",
    slug: "gre-vs-gmat-indian-students-2025-2",
    excerpt: "GRE vs GMAT for Indian students abroad 2025: Compare scores, fees in INR, university acceptance & career impact. Make the right choice today.",
    content: "<h2>GRE vs GMAT for Indian Students Abroad 2025: Which Test Should You Take?</h2>\n\n<p>Over <strong>52,000 Indian students</strong> took either the GRE or GMAT in 2024-2025, making this one of the most critical decisions for your overseas education journey. The choice between GRE vs GMAT for Indian students abroad 2025 directly impacts your university options, scholarship chances, and career trajectory. Let's break down what matters for your decision.</p>\n\n<h3>Why Choose GRE or GMAT?</h3>\n\n<p><strong>GRE (Graduate Record Exam):</strong> Accepted by 1,200+ universities worldwide, including top MBA programs now. GRE works for Master's degrees across engineering, data science, business, and humanities. With 38,000+ Indian test-takers annually, it's the flexible choice for multiple career paths.</p>\n\n<p><strong>GMAT (Graduate Management Admission Test):</strong> The gold standard for MBA programs globally. Preferred by 2,000+ business schools including IIMs and top US universities. Around 14,000 Indian students choose GMAT yearly, with stronger ROI for business careers.</p>\n\n<h3>Top 3 Universities Accepting GRE and GMAT</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Stanford University (QS Rank: 5)</strong> \u2013 Accepts both; GRE median: 164 Quant, GMAT: 730+</li>\n<li><strong>University of Oxford (QS Rank: 3)</strong> \u2013 GMAT required for MBA; GRE accepted for Master's</li>\n<li><strong>National University of Singapore (QS Rank: 8)</strong> \u2013 Both accepted; average GMAT 680+ for Indian students</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Test Fees & Costs in INR (2025)</h3>\n\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; margin:20px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background-color:#f5f5f5;\">\n<th style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px; text-align:left;\"><strong>Expense Item</strong></th>\n<th style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px; text-align:left;\"><strong>GRE Cost</strong></th>\n<th style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px; text-align:left;\"><strong>GMAT Cost</strong></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">Registration Fee</td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">\u20b916,200 ($195 USD)</td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">\u20b919,500 ($235 USD)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">Score Send (4 free, then per school)</td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">\u20b92,500/school (~$30)</td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">\u20b92,800/school (~$33)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">Prep Course (avg)</td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">\u20b935,000-60,000</td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">\u20b940,000-75,000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"background-color:#f9f9f9;\">\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\"><strong>Total (3 attempts + course)</strong></td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\"><strong>\u20b983,700-110,000</strong></td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\"><strong>\u20b9103,300-135,500</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>Best Loan Option for Indian Students</h3>\n\n<p><strong>HDFC Bank Education Loan:</strong> Covers both exam fees and preparation. Interest rate: <strong>9.15%-10.90% p.a.</strong> (2025). Loan amount: Up to \u20b920 lakhs with 15-year repayment. Processing time: 7-10 days. Requires co-applicant (parent/guardian).</p>\n\n<p><strong>SBI Scholar Loan:</strong> Competitive rate at <strong>8.95%-9.65% p.a.</strong> Maximum \u20b930 lakhs. Moratorium period of 6 months post-completion. Popular with 23,000+ Indian students annually.</p>\n\n<h3>Visa: 3 Key Documents Required</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Valid Passport</strong> \u2013 Must have minimum 6 months validity from date of travel</li>\n<li><strong>Score Report</strong> \u2013 Official GRE/GMAT score (older than 5 years not accepted by most universities)</li>\n<li><strong>University Acceptance Letter</strong> \u2013 Conditional or unconditional offer from your chosen institution</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Top Scholarship: Chevening Scholarship 2025-2026</h3>\n\n<p>UK Government-funded scholarship accepting both GRE and GMAT scores. <strong>\u20b925-30 lakhs per year</strong> covering tuition and living costs. 2,000+ awards globally; 180+ for Indian students. Deadline: November 2025 for 2026 intake. GRE minimum: 155+, GMAT: 650+.</p>\n\n<h3>Quick Comparison Facts</h3>\n\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; margin:20px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background-color:#f5f5f5;\">\n<th style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px; text-align:left;\"><strong>Factor</strong></th>\n<th style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px; text-align:left;\"><strong>GRE</strong></th>\n<th style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px; text-align:left;\"><strong>GMAT</strong></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">Test Duration</td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">3 hours 45 mins</td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">3 hours 30 mins</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">Score Range</td>\n<td style=\"border:1px solid #ddd; padding:10px;\">13",
