    title: "Student Accommodation Melbourne 2025: Cost, Areas & Complete Guide",
    slug: "student-accommodation-melbourne-2025-guide",
    excerpt: "Find affordable student accommodation in Melbourne 2025. Compare costs, best areas, booking tips & hidden fees. Guide for international & Indian students.",
    content: "<h2>Melbourne: The Student Hub of Australia</h2><p>Melbourne hosts <strong>170,000+ international students</strong> from over 170 countries, with <strong>12,000+ Indian students</strong> enrolled annually. The city is home to prestigious universities including the University of Melbourne, RMIT, Monash University, and La Trobe University. As Australia's education capital, Melbourne offers world-class facilities, vibrant culture, and diverse accommodation options for students.</p><h2>Types of Student Accommodation in Melbourne 2025</h2><h3>University Halls of Residence</h3><p>On-campus colleges offer community living with meal plans included. <strong>Cost: AUD $250-350/week (\u20b913,500-18,900)</strong>. Pros: Built-in social life, security, furnished. Cons: Limited availability, waiting lists, less independence.</p><h3>Private Build-to-Rent (PBSA)</h3><p>Purpose-built student apartments like UniLodge, Urbanest, and Iglu offer modern amenities. <strong>Cost: AUD $280-400/week (\u20b915,100-21,600)</strong>. Pros: Fully furnished, gyms, study spaces, flexible terms. Cons: Premium pricing, less character.</p><h3>Shared Flats & Houses</h3><p>Renting via flatmates.com.au or Domain.com.au. <strong>Cost: AUD $180-280/week (\u20b99,700-15,100)</strong>. Pros: Most affordable, independence, local experience. Cons: Finding reliable housemates, variable upkeep.</p><h3>Homestay</h3><p>Living with local families. <strong>Cost: AUD $200-300/week (\u20b910,800-16,200)</strong>. Pros: Cultural immersion, meals provided, support. Cons: Less freedom, commute time, limited privacy.</p><h2>Average Rent in Melbourne 2025</h2><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"10\"><tr><th>Accommodation Type</th><th>Weekly Cost (AUD)</th><th>Monthly Cost (INR)</th><th>Annual Cost (INR)</th></tr><tr><td>University Halls</td><td>$250-350</td><td>\u20b91,08,000-1,51,200</td><td>\u20b912,96,000-18,14,400</td></tr><tr><td>PBSA (Modern)</td><td>$280-400</td><td>\u20b91,20,960-1,72,800</td><td>\u20b914,51,520-20,73,600</td></tr><tr><td>Shared Flat</td><td>$180-280</td><td>\u20b977,760-1,20,960</td><td>\u20b993,312-14,51,520</td></tr><tr><td>Homestay</td><td>$200-300</td><td>\u20b986,400-1,29,600</td><td>\u20b91,03,680-15,55,200</td></tr></table><p><em>Conversion: 1 AUD = \u20b954 (2025 rates). Prices vary by proximity to universities.</em></p><h2>Best Accommodation Areas in Melbourne 2025</h2><h3>Parkville (University Hub)</h3><p><strong>Rent: AUD $250-320/week (\u20b913,500-17,280)</strong>. Home to University of Melbourne. Excellent public transport, libraries, caf\u00e9s. Safe, walkable neighborhood with parks. Best for academic access.</p><h3>Carlton (Inner North)</h3><p><strong>Rent: AUD $220-300/week (\u20b911,880-16,200)</strong>. Close to RMIT and Melbourne Uni. Vibrant, multicultural area with Indian restaurants and grocers. Good nightlife, budget-friendly. 15-minute tram ride to CBD.</p><h3>Southbank</h3><p><strong>Rent: AUD $300-400/week (\u20b916,200-21,600)</strong>. Premium riverside location near RMIT. Cultural precincts, galleries, restaurants. Safe, modern buildings. Higher cost but walkable to everything.</p><h3>Brunswick (Trendy & Affordable)</h3><p><strong>Rent: AUD $190-260/week (\u20b910,260-14,040)</strong>. Hipster neighborhood with caf\u00e9s, markets. 20-minute tram to CBD. Lower costs, diverse community. Growing student population.</p><h3>Clayton (Monash University)</h3><p><strong>Rent: AUD $160-240/week (\u20b98,640-12,960)</strong>. Direct access to Monash Clayton campus. Suburban, quieter, excellent for focused studying. Limited nightlife, but safe and spacious.</p><h2>What's Included in Melbourne Accommodation Rent?</h2><ul><li><strong>Furnished units:</strong> Bed, desk, chair, basic kitchen appliances, wardrobes</li><li><strong>Utilities (usually separate):</strong> Electricity, gas, internet\u2014budget AUD $40-80/month (\u20b92,160-4,320)</li><li><strong>University halls:</strong> Meals (some), internet, gym access, social events</li><li><strong>PBSA:</strong> Furnished, utilities bundled, common areas, cleaning services</li><li><strong>Shared flats:</strong> Highly variable\u2014clarify before signing</li></ul><h2>How to Book: Platforms & Timeline</h2><p><strong>Top Booking Platforms:</strong> Student Accommodation Service (SAS), UniLodge, Domain.com.au, flatmates.com.au, Airbnb (short-term). Booking opens <strong>12-18 months in advance</strong> for university housing. Apply for student visas by <strong>May-June</strong> to secure accommodation by <strong>July-August</strong>.</p><p><strong>Red Flags:</strong> Requests for payment via wire transfer before viewing, no lease agreement, prices significantly below market, unprofessional communication.</p><h2>Hidden Costs Every Student Must Know</h2><ul><li><strong>Security Deposit:</strong> 4-6 weeks' rent\u2014usually refunded if no damage (AUD $1,000-2,400 / \u20b954,000-1,29,600)</li><li><strong>Guarantor Fee:</strong> If using guarantor service\u2014AUD $200-400 (\u20b910,800-21,600)</li><li><strong>Utilities Not Included:</strong> Internet, electricity, gas\u2014AUD $100-150/month (\u20b95,400-8,100)</li><li><st",
